@1001=~If you wish my answer then reveal yourself! Who and where are you?~
@1002=~Who I am is unimportant, and where I am is right next to you. Can you not tell that I am invisible? You must have lived a truly sheltered life if you've never come across one such as me. No matter. I see that your face fits the picture perfectly. I have come seeking your head, and I will take it right now!~
@1051=~Slythe,
The time to strike is now. When the party commences on the night of my coronation, you will join up with Kraden, Ranash, Abrich, Onagur, Churask, and Nerrus, six of my greatest doppelganger assassins. You are to insinuate yourself into the crowd in the ballroom. When I have finished my speech, you will strike. If you aren't there, my doppelgangers will proceed without you, and your payment will be forfeit. Make sure to keep a leash on your little bitch of a wife. An invitation to the party is included with this note.

Sarevok

(This looks to be an important note, one that you should hold on to.)~
@1101=~An interesting piece o' material you got there. Greater Ankheg, if I'm not mistaken. Been a while since I seen the like, but if I remember correctly, it makes a fine set of armor. If properly treated it's sturdier than full plate and less than a quarter of the weight! If you're willing to part with your shells I'll give you 2,500 gold for the lot of them. No more can I offer with business as slow as it is. Iron shortage hurting us all.~
@1102=~Ah, this will make a fine suit of plate for a governor or better. Nobility like exotic materials and don't care much about the price. Probably close to 100,000 gold for a tenday's work when I'm finished. I may survive this iron shortage after all.~
@1103=~Whoa! Iron is not so scarce as to make me that desperate! 2,500 gold or nothing, and you can take it or leave it!~
@1104=~Hello again! Still have that greater ankheg shell I see. Have you reconsidered my offer for it? 2,500 gold is fair.~
@1105=~It's you again. I am afraid I'm no longer interested in the greater ankheg shell ye possess. I can tell by the sight of it that it's begun to rot. You'll not get 1 gold for it now, let alone 2,500. What a shame.~
@1106=~A shame it is. It could bring quite a bit once finished. How about this? For 20,000 gold I'll make it into plate for you instead. It's half my normal rate for working on an exotic, but, as I mentioned, business is slow.~
@1107=~Back again, are you? Well, which will it be? Sell me the shell for 2,500, or do I make you armor for 20,000?~
@1108=~A fair price for the workmanship of Taerom Thunderhammer. 20,000 gold it is.~
@1109=~20,000 gold is ridiculous! It would be cheaper to make it from the gold itself!~
@1110=~Here's your 20,000. Make me a suit of armor to be proud of.~
@1111=~On second thought, I am desperately in need of the armor now. I happen to get stabbed a lot. How about I give you 25,000 gp to have it done tomorrow?~
@1112=~Journal entry:
An Offer from Taerom
Taerom "Thunderhammer" of Beregost will pay me 2,500 gold for every greater ankheg shell that I find.~
@1113=~Journal entry:
A Small Fortune!
One lousy ankheg shell for 2,500 gold? I can't believe everyone isn't out hunting those giant bug monsters.~
@1114=~Journal entry:
An Offer from Taerom
For 20,000 gold, Taerom "Thunderhammer" can make me a new suit of plate mail from that greater ankheg shell I found. Also, he says there's a 5,000 gold bounty on a madman named Bassilus. Coincidence? I think not.~
@1115=~Just back from an ankheg frenzy across the river and a bit south. They're in one of their boom cycles, I guess. With iron all shot to hell, there's a good market for greater ankheg armor these days. Bring me back a greater ankheg shell and I'll trade you my axe for it.~
@1116=~Fine work. I'll give you my axe for all of your greater ankheg heads.~
@1117=~Journal entry:
Ankheg Culling
In west Baldur's Gate, a sturdy old dwarf by the name of Fenten has promised to give his axe in exchange for the shell of a greater ankheg. Apparently there's one of them to the south of the city, across the river.~
@1118=~Journal entry:
Ankheg Culling
In exchange for our greater ankheg shells, Fenten gave us his axe as promised.~
@1119=~Good work for killing those ankhegs while sticking to the quota. You can have my staff; it's going to stop functioning soon anyway. Go find yourself a room in the city and rest up. You've earned it.~
@1120=~Journal entry:
Ankheg Culling
Ankhegs are tough to kill, but Gerde's staff is a welcome reward.~
@1121=~This is exactly what I need. Irlentree and Zorl are obviously shapeshifters! I want you to track down and kill every one of them.~
@1122=~There are still more rakshasas. We won't be safe until you've killed them all.~
@1123=~Journal entry:
Investigating the Merchants' League Estate
After dealing with the rakshasas, I reported to Aldeth Sashenstar, who gave me a sword baneful to shapeshifters. Perhaps he should have given it to me BEFORE I faced the rakshasas!~
@1124=~Well done, if I do say so myself! A fine bit of burglary with no unnecessary attention brought to yourself. You can have this sword as a reward. In addition, my Halruaan contact Resar would like to speak with you.~
@1125=~A very expensive setback you have cost us! Your incompetence means counterfeit ships in ports by year's end! A more profound dishonor to the brilliant craftsmen of my land I cannot imagine! Protests from our statesmen will be launched, and your local governor will be made to see our point of view. In the between, all record of this furtive attempt will be erased. Apologies, but you must die!~ [RESAR01]
@1126=~The recovery of our secret is most welcome, but the scrutiny your actions bring will do much damage. I must erase all knowledge of this plan by removing all expendable people. This unfortunately means you. Apologies, but you must die!~ [RESAR01]
@1127=~Alatos was most assuring in his description of your abilities. Right he was, and it is unfortunate I must close all loose ends. This includes potential loose tongues, and, though talented, you are also expendable. Apologies, but you must die!~ [RESAR01]
@1128=~This was risky venture from the start, and though you have undoubtedly slowed ship building, they will now be on guard. Further thievery is impossible, so now to expensive diplomacy. All record of this attempt must be destroyed, including all those expendable. Apologies, but you must die!~ [RESAR01]
@1129=~Tazok did not send thee? Then thou art dead. Help, my minions, HEEELLLPPP!~ [MULAH07]
@1130=~I yield, I yield to thee! Accept my surrender?~ [MULAH02]
@1131=~Fools, you'll never have the chance to take anything! Minions, come forth and kill the intruders!~ [MULAH03]
@1132=~Thanks be to you! Here is an enchanted bow that might help you on your journeys.~
@1133=~They did quite a number on me, those half-ogres. Those brutes are nearly impossible to hit. There's a band of them fortifying themselves in the mountains south-southwest of here... If you could give them a taste of justice, that would do me proud.~
@1134=~Fine work! News of the battle has reached me even here. In an effort to encourage such deeds of righteousness, allow me to present to you my magical gloves... The Sword Coast needs more heroes of your sort, especially in times as dark as these.~
@1135=~Journal entry:
Half-ogres Near Beregost
Bjornin is as generous as he is brave. For my efforts against the half-ogres, he gave me his magical gloves.~
@1136=~<CHARNAME>! I have received news that you have cleared out the Firewine Bridge ruins! No longer will kobolds plague our tiny village. I must congratulate you on a job well done. Everyone is grateful for your help. Take this sling as a show of our gratitude.~
@1137=~A job done well in every respect, and no finer a specimen could I have wished for. By far, she is the most elusive spell component I have ever had to seek. Her body will yield a score of human control potions, as well as a cloak of bravery! I am assured wealth for this season and next at the very least, and I have you to thank. You please have this item and enjoy, yes. It is a good thing you do here today. Show yourselves out, I have much work to attend to.~
@1138=~It is unfortunate that I could only tap some of her resources, but at least I managed to get the cloak out of her; now I must look for another. Maybe... no. I have no time to waste with you right now, so could you kindly be on your way?~
@1139=~You will be paid with a powerful magical amulet for this service.~
@1140=~Thank you for returning with the Helm of Balduran. It was so good to do business together. Here is the amulet, and I shall take the helm. Now I must be off, I'll leave you with some of my servants to escort you out. My servants aren't known for their gentle nature, so I would leave as soon as possible.~
@1141=~Yeah, yeah. Lay off the short-guy jokes, they're older than your grandmother's uncle. The damn blade ain't worth nothing. It's a pride thing. If ya wipe 'is arse with it, I'll give ya a magic sword of mine. Its magic is double edged and no one wants to buy it from me.~
@1142=~Bah, the sword ain't worth the tin she's made from. If ya seal that yappin' mouth of 'is for good, I'll give ya a magic sword of mine. Its magic is double edged and no one wants to buy it from me.~
@1143=~Hmph. Figured maybe he'd eaten it by now. I hope you ran 'im through once or twice to get it, at least. Now take your sword and be gone.~
@1144=~There's been something killing peoples in and 'round the farms here. Zombies or something. I can understands if you can't stomach the task but, just between you an' me real personal-likes, I don't know who else is gonna do it... All of us haves been goin' for a week now without sleep. We've counted twenty zombies or so, so keep track as you kill 'em, if that's what you plans on doing. Once you got 'em all, come back here and I'll gives you the 150 gold pieces that some of us have pooled together. One of us is also offering a pair of boots; he says it's magic but I haves no idea.~
@1145=~Thanks, that's been real generous of yous. Maybe we all can finally get a wink o' sleep yet. Here's that 150 gold pieces and the boots we promised yous. If we hads more, we'd gives 'em to you.~
@1146=~There's a jester by the name of Binky staying at the carnival in Nashkel. He wears a magical cloak and I need you to get your larcenous hands on it and bring it back to me. I assure you that your reward will be handsome. Try not to kill him, just filch it off his person.~
@1147=~Ah, thank you so much. Here is 150 gold pieces and a magic bow for your efforts.~
@1148=~Oh, I do like your handiwork. Here is 200 gold pieces and a magic bow for the trouble.~
@1149=~Do you have Binky's cloak with you?~
@1150=~Journal entry:
Binky's Cloak
The dwarf Pheirkas wants me to steal a cloak from a jester named Binky, who I can find at the carnival in Nashkel. Pheirkas awaits the cloak in the northwest section of Baldur's Gate.~
@1151=~Thanks and long live the foolish! Here's 500 gold pieces for taking care of that on such short notice. Also, you might want this. It's a cloak I obtained from a fence I know in Athkatla.~
@1152=~So, you have proved yourself to be of some use after all. As I told you, Gervisse was a dirty old man and this city is safer without him. Here, allow me to give this ring as a... thank you for services rendered.~
@1153=~They're Doom Kobolds, dozens of them. They captured me and stripped me down. The dirty imps tortured me with their insects, but I got away. They'll be here soon. We have to run, get out of here.~
@1154=~Ah, the iron mine in the Cloakwood? So you're the one who wiped it clean? Congratulations and well achieved. My friend Gretek and his party are coming here soon. They'll be so excited to hear your tale.~
@1155=~Wait, I recognize you! You're the hero of Nashkel and the liberator of mines there and here! Stay for a time; my friend Gretek will want to meet you.~
@1156=~<CHARNAME>! We've found you! Battle after battle you have won against the Iron Throne, but this battle you will not. Ready yourself!~
@1157=~Fight if you want, but you are veritably outmatched. I have a friendly band of Merry Fools excited to leap to my defense.~
@1158=~I don't care to indulge a group of jabbering idiots. Take your death threats elsewhere.~
@1159=~There are no Merry Fools to leap to your side any longer, because I killed the last of them a day ago. We have waited for you to settle in this tavern, and you have fallen right into our trap. Sorry to say, but you are the one who is outmatched!~
@1160=~My thanks for your carelessness to your own survival! If you have no wish to fight then that makes what comes next all the easier!~
@1161=~You there! State your business, but don't move from where you stand! I don't want to have to sic the umber hulks on you!~
@1162=~You found my gauntlets! I was beginning to think they'd never show up. Here, take this quiver as your reward. I'm sure you'll have a use for it some time.~
@1165=~Time to go home, Rufie. You'll like the Bleak Eternity much better than these cold climes.~
@1166=~Demons in the Mines

Unfortunately, the rumors were true. There are demons in these mines. I should go further into these mines and find the source of the demons.~
@1167=~Heh, ye're a wonder, you are. Stick with me and we'll go far... Well, okay, stick with me and we'd prob'ly never leave the walls of Candlekeep, would we...? They say the bandits out there aren't after gold and gems anymore but just plain old iron. It's one of them whatchamacallits, paradoxes or whatever: It's dangerous, so you want to wear some good solid plate and carry an axe that'd make Tempus jealous, but rather than protectin' ya, it just makes everyone want a piece of you, right? And supposedly them bandits can shoot an arrow straight through armor. Given my druthers, I guess I'd rather stay right here...~
@1168=~Heh, ye're a wonder, you are. Stick with me and we'll go far... Well, okay, stick with me and we'd prob'ly never leave the walls of Candlekeep, would we...? Hmm, good thing you ain't wearin' none of that metal armor though, as I hear that the bandits out there would just as soon kill you as look at you to get it off your back. And them bandits are said to be so accurate they can shoot an arrow straight through metal armor! I just hope this whole iron crisis business is wrapped up soon.~
@1169=~*sob*... Pixie, my cat, she turned a bird into a rat and fell into the water chasing it... *sniff*... I hope she's all right.~
@1170=~Thanks for saving Arabelle here. Ever since them xvarts an' their kobold kin swarmed the mines at Nashkel, they've been makin' attacks like that more and more often. If someone like yourself could get to the bottom of that, all of us trying to make an honest livin' out here sure would be grateful. Here, take this magic scroll. I don't know what it does.~
@1171=~The favor I ask of you is a simple one. The holy day Storm Call approaches. It will be the first time I have overseen this ceremony. To ensure that my first ceremony is flawless, I need an item of power. It is called the Tome of Wondrous Fortune, and it is possessed by the clergy of Tymora at the Temple of Tymora, called the Lady's Hall by those who venerate the frivolous goddess. If you can get this book for me, I will do what you ask. What is your decision?~
@1172=~So, you've returned with the Tome of Wondrous Fortune. Let me see it.~
@1173=~We are in desperate need of a book known as the Tome of Wondrous Fortune. Please, we will do anything if you'd only give it to us.~
@1174=~The Tome of Wondrous Fortune is a very holy book. Why should I give it to the likes of you?~
@1175=~Fear not. I was not presuming to tell thee where to go, for thou art more than capable. I will leave thee to thy travels. But take this book, which will inform thee of some of the dangers thou may encounter. Luck be with thee, for thou've made some vengeful enemies: some that thou've yet to meet, and some as close as thine own heart. ~
@1176=~As thou hast no doubt determined, the clues seem to point towards the Cloakwood forest. 'Tis likely that the scoundrels behind the bandits have some sort of base within the wood. Of course, I am only telling thee things that thou dost already know. Good luck on thy travels, young one. Be wary as well, for thou art making powerful enemies, both here... and within thyself. I am sorry I cannot speak more plainly on this matter, but events must unfold as they will without any meddling from this old man. As a final act of guidance, thou may have this book, which will inform thee of some of the dangers that lie ahead.~
@1301=~It is a surprise to find such beautiful people coming into this seedy place. All of you look rather weary, down on your times I might say. Why don't I treat you to some refreshments, perhaps some Berduskan amber wine?~
@1302=~Sorry if I seem out of breath, but I am still recovering from an earlier battle. I was ambushed by a dozen gnolls a little while ago. I handily dispatched them but thought better of fighting their half dozen ogre friends. I think I'm safe from them here. Would any of you care for a drink of some fine Selgauntian brandy?~
@1303=~Every so often, I will ask you if you've had enough. If you have, then I shall teleport you back outside. If you wish to continue practicing, however, then I shall create some more illusions for you to fight. Are you ready then? Good, here we go! I will start by summoning some gibberlings. Gibberlings can move terribly fast, and they attack in a whirlwind of slashes. They are very dangerous normally, but my illusions will not harm you.~
@1304=~Good! Then I will create some more illusory monsters. This time I'll create some xvarts. Xvarts stop time whenever they move. I have managed to replicate this ability with my illusions.~
@1305=~Good! Then I'll create some more illusory monsters. This time I'm going to create some skeletons. Strike a skeleton and its body will fall apart, but its skull will animate and continue to fight on. Osprey's Magical Stone spell will prevent this effect from happening.~
@1306=~Good! Then I'll create some more illusory monsters. I'm creating kobolds this time. There are many, many different kinds of kobolds, each with their own strange powers. My illusions only replicate one kind.~
@1307=~Good! Then I'll create even more illusory monsters. This time I'll create some tasloi. Looking a tasloi in the eye causes you to go uncontrollably berserk. My illusions have this power as well, though their gaze is easier to resist than that of wild tasloi. Mordaine's robe will protect her from the tasloi's gaze.~
@1308=~Some of your comrades will have magic items. It would be wise to understand what these items do, as even the more generic magic items can have unique powers.~
@1401=~The mask intones: "Ooze splits before fire and lightning, but is destroyed by mundane blows."~
@1402=~The mask intones: "Fire, ice, slime, and wind. All must perish to continue."~
@1403=~How shallow do you think me that I would give up my destiny after a few short words with you? Have you no strength to YOUR convictions? I have no pity for your kind! You will be swept aside! You are already too late, and a new age rises! Behold Aec'Letec, the deadliest of all nabassus! Born of the Abyss, but destined to walk the Prime! The dagger is broken! Behold your new lord and master!~
@1404=~By all that is loud and windy, will you please shut up?! You can pose all you wish, but you have failed! Here will come the new lord, despite your slogans! Here will come the new lord, despite your puny weapons! Here will come the new lord, Aec'Letec, deadliest of all nabassus! Born of the Abyss, let he who was imprisoned walk the Prime! The dagger is broken! I release you!~
@1405=~~
@1601=~I've heard that Amn is going to invade. Those damnable, war-mongering mutton-heads. They're like quicklings, the way those soldiers run about, and no better either. Shoulda seen it coming too. This iron thing has to be all their doing. You ain't from the south, are ya? If you are, then I don't trust ya!~
@1602=~You look a lot like the bandits that raided my caravan! No, maybe it wasn't you. You don't look like you could fire arrows the way they can. This crisis just has me on edge. I see bandits wherever I look. Hope it all ends soon, one way or another.~
@1603=~Nashkel is a rotten town, run by a bunch of priggers and the quicks that call themselves soldiers. Betcha this iron shortage is just another Amnian plot. They would love to get a hold of Baldur's Gate, I just know it.~
@1604=~Hey! Shut your potato trap and give your tongue a holiday. I don't want strangers in my business. Shove off before I start to shoot fire out of my hands.~
@1605=~I bet those rank-ridin' bandits are hired by the Amnian. It'd be like those moneygrubbers to pull something so low. Their own soldier-quicks can barely aim a bow so they hire brigand scum to do it for them...~
@1606=~My son was on one of the caravans that didn't make it to Baldur's Gate. I pray to Tymora that he's all right. May the Lady guide him safely home, and may she rob these bandits of their unholy accuracy. They deserve much worse.~
@1607=~You're pathetic... Okay, I'll rattle it off for you like I did for the last adventurer and the one before that. I have no doubt you'll share their fate. Let's see, there are the ruins of an old mage school to the southeast. Traps, dead things that try to kill you, and creatures of magic itself, supposedly... Then there's the Firewine Bridge: ghosts, minotaurs, winding narrow passageways, some poetry, blah, blah, blah... Honestly, I can't think of a life more tedious than that of an adventurer. Personally, I get far more out of wandering around aimlessly and scratching my arse like this.~
@1608=~Did you hear another Flaming Fist just got killed defending us from bandits? A brigand bowman shot an arrow straight through her plate armor. If the city watch cannot protect us from raids, what am I paying tax for?! I would be better off hiring mercenaries than trying to rely on the city guards. Nobody is fool enough to want to guard my caravans though. Cowards all. Guess I'll just wait out the crisis here.~
@1609=~I was attacked outside the city last week. Was by a gnome with muscles to wrestle a giant, carrying a sword twice his size! Yet he could barely walk without tripping, and I fled faster than he could follow. Every night I fear he could be coming for me.~
@1610=~It will be a cold day in the lower planes before I risk my neck in the elven ruin o' Firewine! I hear a lord of minotaurs makes his home there, and I have no wish to meet such a monster in those tight passages. You can barely stand two abreast in there. Tight enough to be a tomb, and for many a man it is a tomb.~
@1611=~That Ulcaster School was a storehouse of knowledge and magic, but the shadowy spirits that haunt the place are no better for it. Being dead longer than you were alive must tend to addle the mind.~
@1612=~The most dangerous thing I intentionally went after? Stalked a cave bear for a few days once. Had a party of me own back then. Wounded the bear, but then it retaliated like a dragon, consuming my party in waves of fire. Still managed to kill the bear, but not really worth the price of my friends. I've seen more dangerous beasties, but usually over my shoulder as I'm making tracks as fast as I can. No shame in running when your life is on the line. Off with you now, I've meat to catch.~
@1613=~ 'Round here? I wouldn't worry yourself too much, unless you're brainless and charge everything you see. Mostly gibberlings, but they aren't too much of a hassle. Just be sure put an arrow in them before they reach you. Wolves have become a bit more predatory lately. I think it's because more people are hunting for their food, seein' as how the iron shortage took away their normal livelihoods. A hungry wolf is a nasty thing, and I wouldn't travel without a group if I were you. With a group you might stand a better chance of noticing the wolves through their camouflage.~
@1614=~You would do well to know your own limitations. I don't care whether you're a great swords<MANWOMAN> or a powerful wizard. Regardless you will end up filleted in the noonday sun if you do not take proper care. Remember, we are not the only beings with mysterious powers; the beasties of the wild have dangerous abilities as well. Move along, will you? You may be intent on digging an early grave, but I've no wish to share it with you.~
@1615=~Kobolds! Demons, too. They're overrunning the place piece by piece. Both kobolds and demons have been killing us miners. The kobolds and demons don't seem to like each other: I saw a demon kill a kobold. The demons and kobolds both seem to be coming from the lower levels.~
@1616=~Journal entry:
Demons and kobolds have been killing the miners.~
@1617=~We don't have the manpower to patrol the mines, what with the problem of bandits up north. Our shoddy armor hardly matters when a bandit could put an arrow through the best plate mail. We can only hope they don't aim at us...~
@1618=~Travel lightly, wanderer. The woods harbor strange things. I've heard many stories... worm-like creatures harnessing divine magic that can reflect our arrows back at us, monsters that can stop time, and even such a thing as a Greater Ogre. I hope none of these things come to Nashkel, for if they do I will hardly be a match for them.~
@1619=~Move along, citizen. You could be a doppelganger, the way you're coming so close to me. Watch out for doppelgangers in Nashkel right now. We had an encounter with one of them a few days ago, and I suspect there is at least one more of them hiding somewhere in this town.~
@1620=~You heard the rumors flying about town? Supposedly there's a cave to the northeast where there is a giant troll. The adventurer who saw the troll fled as fast as her legs could take her. I hope that troll stays in the cave...~
@1621=~I've lost ten head of cattle in the last month alone! Gall-derned raiders must be gettin' into rustling I figure. My cows crushed some of 'em, but not all.~
@1622=~I swear I saw something moving out back o' my place, so I keep my jumpin' cattle on the watch at night. They be poor guards but I cannot afford any other protection.~
@1623=~How dare you come into my home uninvited! Back in my adventuring days, such an affront would get you a Blade of Disaster in the backside! If 'twere not for social convention I'd give you a right proper disintegration!~
@1624=~Good then. Enjoy your stay. Just a warning, though: we've had shapeshifter trouble recently. It was only a few days ago that a doppelganger murdered a woman at this inn. The stupid fiend did the deed in plain sight. We slew it, but I worry there may be others lurking in disguise. Take my advice: if you encounter a shapeshifter in this inn, flee and ask one of us for help. The guards of the Friendly Arm are professional fighters.~
@1625=~Be careful in your travels, friend; the roads have become exceedingly dangerous. I hate to say it, but this inn is hardly much safer. We've had several encounters with doppelgangers in the inn through the past week. We had no trouble slaying them, but I worry that one might take me by surprise. Now I've become suspicious of every traveller who passes this gate. I wouldn't mistrust you, though.~
@1901=~Will you use the scroll?~
@1902=~Use it.~
@1903=~Put the scroll away.~
@1904=~The walls of Candlekeep are warded to prevent teleportation. You cannot use the scroll right now.~
@1905=~The scroll glows and dissolves as you read it. Moments later, your party is teleported to an unknown location...~
@1906=~The magic of this island prevents teleportation away from it by most means. You cannot use the scroll right now.~
